    "Dr. Peter S. Ruckman": "any more than a postmillennial expositor could, thirty years before World War I. With \u201cadvanced light\u201d and \u201cmore light since 1880,\u201d the Fundamentalists didn\u2019t get enough light to light a cigarette. Kroll doesn\u2019t know when the \u201ctribes\u201d go up (vs.4) and doesn\u2019t know whose \u201cfeet\u201d will stand in Jerusalem (vs. 2). Neither does Motyer, Yates, or Dummelow. But as far as that goes, the hyperdispensationalist Ethelbert Bullinger can\u2019t get it either. Again, Kroll\u2019s conscience gets the best of him, so after blowing it through five verses, he says \u201cto pray for the peace of Jerusalem is to pray that the Prince of Peace will soon establish his kingdom upon this earth with Jerusalem as his capital\u201d (p. 1158). Exactly; but knowing that, Kroll says God\u2019s house used to be there because it was David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s tabernacle. Why couldn\u2019t Kroll see that the house will be there because it will be rebuilt? Couldn\u2019t he read Acts 15? Evidently not. \u201cToday the house of the Lord is a common expression for the church, the place set apart and sanctified for God\u2019s use alone.\u201d You mean \u201cthe church building\u201d? They do have a time of it, don\u2019t they? \u201cThe house of the LORD\u201d (vss. 1, 9) is \u201cthe house of the LORD,\u201d and it will be rebuilt (Ezek. 40\u201346), but Kroll knew nothing about that. Neither did Baethgen, Dummelow, Yates, Delitzsch, Gesenius, Hengstenberg, or anyone who was dumb enough to think that they were Bible believers. The \u201cgates\u201d of\nverse 5, both for \u201cjudgment\u201d and for \u201cthe house of David `[char_David_Rut_4]`.\u201d They make all of them \u201cone judgment seat of David `[char_David_Rut_4]`.\u201d Nuts. \u201cPeace\u201d and \u201cprosperity\u201d (vs. 7) will come to Jerusalem in answer to prayer, so a Gentile who prays for that kingdom to come\u2014a Jewish kingdom at Jerusalem [v_Mat_6_13] (Matt. 6:13)\u2014will prosper in this age (vs. 6). It is Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` Christ Himself who says, \u201cPeace be within thee\u201d (vs. 8), and says this for the sake of his \u201cbrethren\u201d (vs. 8); see [v_Psa_7_7]",
    "Frederick Dale Bruner": "The Cleanest People, 23:25-26 Woe\n5. The Cleanest People, 23:25-26\n5. The Cleanest People, 23:25-26 \"Woe to you Bible teachers and Serious -you phonies! Why, you clean up the outside of cup and plate, but inside they are full because of plunder and uncontrolled sensuality. Blind Separatists! Clean up the inside of the cup first, and then the outside is clean as well.\" The translation of 23:25's ex (\"because of\") is decisive: it gives the cause of the \"fullness\" enjoyed by the religious as most modern exegetes now see (cf., e.g., Blomberg, 347; Hare, 270; Luz, 3335-36, who also points out that the \"uncontrolled sensuality\" here, akrasia, was expressed mainly in sexual lusts but also in immoderate eating). Matthew 15 treated the subject of this and the next Woe [v_Lev_11_33] thoroughly (Stendahl, 793). Lev 11:33 declared unclean any earthen vessel the inside of which had been touched by the ritually unclean. But the Serious, always wishing to be both safe and extra- devoted, went the extra mile and protected the outside from all ritual contamination as well (Goppelt, TDNT, 6:149). Haenchen, 427, believes that our text addresses the spilling of holy wine and that the Serious extended this caution, playing safe, from priests to laity. Both this Woe and the next are directed against a commercialistic spirit that, while it seems to be passionately religious, is in fact passionately possessed with its social appearance and sensual gratification. Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` sees through this obsession with appearance and pleasure, and he sees into the spirit that produced the obsession in the first place. Others have noticed the unity of this pair of Woes (cf. Sand, 460). Because \"plunder,\" an economic sin, and \"uncontrolled sensuality,\" a sexual or physical sin, seem so disparate, early manuscripts offered variations on the second term (pleonexia; cf. the RSV's \"rapacity\"; the NRSV preferred \"self-indulgence\"). But we recall Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`' lambasting \"an evil and adulterous generation\" (12:39; 16:4), and McKenzie, 103, notes helpfully that \"the combination [of [v_Amo_2_6] [v_Amo_2_7] [v_Amo_2_8] economic and sexual sins] does echo Amos 2:6-8\" Luz, 3:337, contends that Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` speaks here of acts, not attitudes, and so prefers the translation \"rip-off\" to the usual \"greed.\" Orthodox religion of several types still gives itself to ceremonial cleanliness, for example, by meticulous attention to meals and offerings. The word \"outside\" here may mean either the literal outside of a cup (thus Goppelt) TDNT, 6:149) or, symbolically, the external devotions of piety (McNeile) 336, prefers the latter; Meier, 271, sees the former transferring to the latter). Ironically, the Serious Pharisees regularly criticized the Sophisticated Sadducees for rip-off and sensualism, but Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` says that in the depths these were characteristics of the Serious as well (Bonnard) 341; Haenchen, 427, believes this Woe is false because it criticizes Pharisaism for well-known Sadduceeisms; but aren't our opponents' more obvious faults sometimes our own hidden ones?). But no matter how clean the cup externally and ceremonially, the problem lay with the cup's contents. (i) What is inside the immaculate cup and plate was acquired by plunder (harpage), that is, by wheeling and dealing, by cheating (particularly, by dishonest methods in business, Schlatter, Der Evangelist, 681; Haenchen, 427; Luz, 3:337), and by greed (for the violence inside the word harpage, see Bauer, WB, 215). And (2) what is inside the spotless cup and plate was acquired by means of and for the sake of uncontrolled sensuality (akrasia), that is, by and for hedonistic pleasure (akrasia means, literally, lack of self-control, Bauer, WB, 64-65; Klostermann, 187; Schlatter, Der Evangelist, 681; Goppelt, TDNT, 6:149; Haenchen, 427). Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` is an economic prophet in this Woe, as he had been in chap.\n5. Cf. Jer 7:13-15, and in particular 12:",
    "Commentary Vol. 83": "And the children of Heth answered Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]`, etc.] In a very civil and respectful manner: saying unto him, as follows:\nVer.",
    "Warren W. Wiersbe": "Isaac prayed \u201cnot to get [his] will done in heaven but to get God\u2019s will done on earth.\u201d What are some things God wants us to pray for in this way?\nv. 5). When Isaac sent for Esau to come to his tent, Rebekah noticed it and stayed close by to learn what was happening. Later, when Esau revealed that he planned to kill his brother, Rebekah also heard that (\n5. How did Esau continue to demonstrate his worldly mindedness?\n5. How could these verses apply to the disappointment Jacob felt after having married Leah: Proverbs 21:30 [c_Pro_21] [v_Pro_21_30] ; Genesis 50:20 [c_Gen_50] [v_Gen_50_20] ; Romans 8:28 [c_Rom_8] [v_Rom_8_28] ?\n5. Have you ever been afraid of dealing with a person or situation? How did you handle that situation? Did you act with faith or lack of it?"
