    "Craig S. Keener": "To accomplish this purpose in the face of the ever- increasing number of secondary resources, I have made use of abstracts where necessary on numerous points not central to my examination, just as many commentaries list more works in their segmented bibliographies than they actually cite in their text. Although it is no longer possible to be exhaustive, my purpose here is to provide the reader with a brief idea of other resources she or he may pursue further.\n7. For traditions and arguments for Mark's use of Petrine material, see ACCS, xxi-xxviii; Hengel 1991: 238-43; cf. Feldmeier 1991: 252-56.",
    "Dr. Peter S. Ruckman": "The city of Samaria had been besieged by the Syrians, and the inhabitants were starving to death. Outside the gate sat three lepers. They were dying slowly from leprosy, and with the siege, they were dying more quickly from starvation. They decided to go to the camp of the Syrians and beg for food. They figured that the worst that could happen to them would be that the Syrians would kill them. When they arrived at the Syrian camp, they found it deserted because God had caused the Syrians to hear a great noise which they thought was a mercenary army coming to break the siege. The Syrians had all fled in a panic and had left everything, including all their food, behind. Well, those three lepers stuffed themselves silly, and after they had made two or three trips to stash away some food and other goodies for a \u201crainy day,\u201d they got under terrible conviction. \u201c Then they said one to another, We do not well: this day is a day of good tidings, and we hold our peace: if we tarry till the morning light, some mischief will come upon us: now therefore come, that we may go and tell the king\u2019s household\u201d (2 Kings 7:9). If you are a Christian who does not witness, you \u201cdo not well.\u201d You know where the good food is, and you are selfishly keeping it to yourself. \u201cSome mischief\u201d is going to come upon you if you do not open your mouth for Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` Christ. 9 I have compared thee, O my love, to a company of horses in Pharaoh\u2019s chariots. 10 Thy cheeks are comely with rows of jewels, thy neck with chains of gold. 11 We will make thee borders of gold with studs of silver. 12 While the king sitteth at his table, my spikenard sendeth forth the smell thereof. 13 A bundle of myrrh is my wellbeloved unto me; he shall lie all night betwixt my breasts. 14 My beloved is unto me as a cluster of camphire in the vineyards of Engedi. The King is speaking here, for sure, because he makes a reference to \u201ca company of horses in Pharaoh\u2019s chariots\u201d (vs. 9). Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` has \u201ca company of horses,\u201d and he got them from Pharaoh. \u201c And Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` had horses brought out of Egypt...And a chariot came up and went out of Egypt for six hundred shekels of silver, and an horse for an hundred and fifty\u201d (1 Kings 10:28\u201329). \u201c And Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` had four thousand stalls for horses and chariots...And they brought unto Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` horses out of Egypt\u201d (2 Chron. 9:25, 28). The Hebrew word for horses , in\n7. The city of Samaria had been besieged by the Syrians, and the inhabitants were starving to death. Outside the gate sat three lepers. They were dying slowly from leprosy, and with the siege, they were dying more quickly from starvation. They decided to go to the camp of the Syrians and beg for food. They figured that the worst that could happen to them would be that the Syrians would kill them. When they arrived at the Syrian camp, they found it deserted because God had caused the Syrians to hear a great noise which they thought was a mercenary army coming to break the siege. The Syrians had all fled in a panic and had left everything, including all their food, behind. Well, those three lepers stuffed themselves silly, and after they had made two or three trips to stash away some food and other goodies for a \u201crainy day,\u201d they got under terrible conviction. \u201cThen they said one to another, We do not well: this day is a day of good tidings, and we hold our peace: if we tarry till the morning light, some mischief will come upon us: now therefore come, that we may go and tell the king\u2019s household\u201d (2 Kings 7:9). If you are a Christian who does not witness, you \u201cdo not well.\u201d You know where the good food is, and you are selfishly keeping it to yourself. \u201cSome mischief\u201d is going to come upon you if you do not open your mouth for Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` Christ. 9 I have compared thee, O my love, to a company of horses in Pharaoh\u2019s chariots. 10 Thy cheeks are comely with rows of jewels, thy neck with chains of gold. 11 We will make thee borders of gold with studs of silver. 12 While the king sitteth at his table, my spikenard sendeth forth the smell thereof. 13 A bundle of myrrh is my wellbeloved unto me; he shall lie all night betwixt my breasts. 14 My beloved is unto me as a cluster of camphire in the vineyards of Engedi. The King is speaking here, for sure, because he makes a reference to \u201ca company of horses in Pharaoh\u2019s chariots\u201d (vs. 9). Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` has \u201ca company of horses,\u201d and he got them from Pharaoh. \u201cAnd Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` had horses brought out of Egypt...And a chariot came up and went out of Egypt for six hundred shekels of silver, and an horse for an [v_1Ki_10_28] hundred and fifty\u201d (1 Kings 10:28\u201329). \u201cAnd Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` had four thousand stalls for horses and chariots...And they brought unto Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` [v_2Ch_9_25] horses out of Egypt\u201d (2 Chron. 9:25, 28). The Hebrew word for horses, in",
    "Frederick Dale Bruner": "The Defenders of the Faith, 2329-33 III. Conclusion: The Future of the Ancient People of God, 2334-39 A. The Indictment of Israel, 23:34-36 B. The Lament over Jerusalem, 23:37-39\n7. But unlike Jeremiah, Ezekiel, Hosea, or even Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]`, Matthew's Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`' pessimism is hard because it seems terminal, not temporary (Hare, 148-49,151,153). Jeremiah, Ezekiel, Hosea, and Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]` saw hope ahead for Israel. It is difficult to see hope ahead for Israel in Matthew unless it is present cryptically in the last verse of the chapter, to which we now come. 23:39 `I tell you, in fact, from now on you will never ever see me again until the day you say, `Blessed is he who comes in the name [v_Psa_118_26] of the Lord.\"' See Ps 118:26 and cf. Matt 21:",
    "Commentary Vol. 83": "And Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]` stood up, etc.] For, having made his speech to the children of Heth, he sat down waiting for an answer; or rather perhaps they obliged him to sit down, out of reverence to so great a personage; and when they had done speaking, he rose up: and bowed himself to the people of the land; the principal of them, in token of the grateful sense he had of the honour they had done him, and of the great civility with which they had used him: [even] to the children of Heth; this seems to be added to distinguish them from the common people, and as an explanation of the preceding clause; [v_Gen_23_3] (see Gill on \u201c<012303>Genesis 23:3\u201d).\nVer.",
    "Warren W. Wiersbe": "Why would God bless people who live less-than-perfect lives?\n7. Can you remember episodes in your life where you did what you thought was right but in the wrong way? How did it turn out?\n7. Wiersbe says the Lord speaks to believers by placing certain desires in their hearts, by placing certain circumstances in their paths, and most important, through His Word. What has God been telling you through these three means?\n7. What was the significance of Jacob\u2019s name change? What should God\u2019s statement in 32:28 have meant to Jacob?"
